‚úîÔ∏è What you want

A numeric field should use a numeric filter (eq, gte, lte, etc.) instead of string filters.

‚úîÔ∏è How to force Telerik to use numeric filtering

Add .Filterable(ft => ft.Cell(cell => cell.Operator("eq")))
OR explicitly set the filter UI to numeric.

Example:

c.Bound(v => v.VehicleListId)
 .Title("Estimate #")
 .Filterable(f => f.UI("numericFilter"))
 .Width(120);


Then add a small JS helper:

function numericFilter(element) {
    element.kendoNumericTextBox({
        format: "n0",
        decimals: 0
    });
}

Result?

Your column uses numeric filtering, and the operator dropdown now becomes:

Is equal to

Is not equal to

Is greater than

Is less than
‚Ä¶etc.

No more string operators like ‚Äúcontains.‚Äù

‚úÖ 2. Highlight the column filter icon when the column is filtered

Yes ‚Äî totally possible. Telerik exposes a class when a column has an active filter.

Telerik automatically adds:

k-filtered to the column header when a filter is applied.

üëç Simplest approach: Add CSS to highlight the filter icon
.k-grid th.k-filtered .k-grid-filter {
    color: #0078d7;      /* nice blue highlight */
    font-weight: bold;
}


If you want a background highlight around the whole header:

.k-grid th.k-filtered {
    background-color: #e6f3ff;
}

No JS needed ‚Äî Telerik handles toggling the class for you.
